Team Bayelsa emerged the overall winner of the maiden National Para Sports Festival held at the Moshood Abiola National Stadium, Abuja. After six days of sports artistry and fights for medals, Team Bayelsa amassed a total of 93 medals, comprising 31 gold, 30 silver and 32 bronze medals, to finish top on the medal log ahead of other participating states. Team Oyo finished second on the medals log with  60 medals of 24 gold, 15 silver and 21 bronze. While Team Kano came third with 42 medals consisting 21 gold, 13 silver and 8 bronze medals. Team Edo, Ondo, Imo and FCT occupied 4th, 5th, 6th and 7th positions respectively on the final medal table released by the organisers. On the final day of competition, Deaf Soccer thrilled spectators with splendour in the gold medal match as Team Abia beat Team Nasarawa 1-0 to pick gold. Speaking at the closing ceremony, Sports Minister Sunday Dare expressed joy with the staging of the festival and the level of competitiveness at the Games. He said the athletes have always been deserving of a festival like this as their contribution to Nigeria’s image internationally is awe-inspiring. The Minister who was represented by permanent secretary, Ministry of Youth and Sports Development, Alhaji Ismaila Abubakar, thanked all contingents present and promised a bigger festival going forward. He reiterated the commitment of the federal government to the welfare of special athletes as attested to by the creation of a special department for para athletes. The 2nd edition of the National Para Games is expected to take place next year, and thereafter, every two years. Twenty-one (21) states participated in the maiden Games as their athletes delivered style and skills for six days in 15 different sports.